<TEXT>
hurricane kiko slammed into the baja 
california peninsula with 115 mph winds that blew down homes and 
forced hundreds of people to evacuate but it lost strength sunday 
as it passed over hilly terrain 
after striking the southeastern coast of the peninsula and 
driving toward the pacific ocean the storms top sustained winds 
fell to 90 mph by 5 am 8 am edt the national weather service 
in miami said 
kiko bore down hardest on la rivera a city of 4000 people 75 
miles south of la paz said lt ignacio cortez telechea assistant 
state government director there were homes of thin wood and 
laminated cardboard that blew down he said they had palm or 
cardboard roofs that blew away trees antennas electrical poles 
fell 
there were no immediate reports of injuries but more than 300 
people left their homes and were housed in shelters in the area 
officials said 
sgt ruben burgoin peralta the police officer on duty in san 
jose del cabo said 20 homes were destroyed in la rivera which is 
in his district 
at 5 am the storm was located near latitude 237 north and 
longitude 1105 west or 35 miles south of la paz the capital of 
baja california is 760 miles south of san diego the storm was 
moving west at about 5 mph said the national weather service 
the weather bulletin said kiko hit the coast at midnight saturday 
and lost strength as it struck the coastal cliffs and high terrain 
of the peninsula 
the weather service said hurricane warnings were in effect for 
the gulf of california side of the baja peninsula from the southern 
tip northward to bahia conception 200 miles north of la paz they 
were also declared for the pacific side south of san carlos 
bob case a hurricane specialist at the national hurricane center 
in coral gables fla said the worst of kiko is over for baja 
the biggest problem is continued heavy rains flash floods and 
mudslides he said in a telephone interview early sunday 
it should come out over the open waters of the pacific during 
the day and resume a westnorthwest track and we expect it to 
continually weaken as it heads over cooler waters in the next day or 
two he said 
the storm also lashed buenavista and other small towns south of 
la paz on the coast of the sparsely populated state and sent water 
rushing down normally dry gullies stopping traffic along the 
highway from san jose del cabo to la paz officials said 
electricity was out from cabo san lucas at the tip of the 
peninsula up the coast to towns south of la paz the lack of power 
also cut water service since pumps are electric 
antonio alvarez acevedo the san jose del cabo public security 
director said the few hotels along the coast around la rivera had 
not been evacuated 
they are the type of construction that can take it he said 
francisco zatarain the state public security coordinator said 
emergency supplies were being mustered and shelters stocked with 
food and blankets throughout the state storm warnings were being 
broadcast civil defense units had been mobilized and military units 
were standing by he said 
the airline aeromexico canceled or diverted service to los 
mochis mazatlan and la paz on saturday after making an early 
morning flight to the three cities the reservations office said 
