wisconsin bell and the union representing some 
4200 striking workers reached a tentative settlement early sunday 
but the workers would stay off the job until their counterparts in 
other midwestern states reached settlements a spokesman said 
the settlement came a day after workers at ohio bell also reached 
a tentative contract both state companies are subsidiaries of the 
fivestate ameritech regional telephone company which has been 
strikebound since aug 13 
we are still on strike until all bargaining tables with 
ameritech are resolved hugh walsh president of communication 
workers of america local 4603 said in a tape recorded message to 
union members announcing the wisconsin settlement 
wisconsin bell spokesman vyto kapocius confirmed the settlement 
but declined to comment further saying the company would reveal the 
details at an afternoon news conference 
some 37000 cwa workers at ameritech subsidiaries in illinois 
ohio indiana michigan and wisconsin walked off the job aug 13 
the regional telephone company one of the socalled baby bells 
created by the breakup of atampt in 1984 is based in chicago 
the ameritech strike is one of four that began earlier this 
month involving a total of 200000 workers in 20 states and the 
district of columbia 
unions have negotiated tentative settlements with striking 
employees at pacific telesis which serves california and nevada 
and bell atlantic which covers west virginia virginia maryland 
delaware pennsylvania new jersey and thedistrict of columbia 
in new york nynex corp said friday it had agreed to resume 
bargaining with its striking workers for the first formal talks 
since that walkout started almost three weeks ago that regional 
company serves new york and most of new england 
