<TEXT>
delegates to the first assembly of the 
evangelical lutheran church in america on sunday delayed a decision 
on whether to set a deadline for selling off stock in companies 
doing business in south africa 
after some debate the decision was deferred until later in the 
eightday meeting of about 1040 representatives which runs through 
wednesday 
at issue was how rapidly the churchs board of pensions should 
divest from such companies to push south africa to end its system of 
racial separation and domination of 28 million blacks by 5 million 
whites 
after morning worship services in chicagoarea churches around 
this suburb the delegates spent more than three hours discussing 
other aspects of the pension program including medical benefits 
and the south african issue 
there is no way one can prudently divest the portfolio except 
gradually over a long period of time it must be handled with care 
and fiduciary responsibility said board president john kapanke of 
minneapolis 
but the pension members for justice a group on the other side of 
the issue said the church has an ethical responsibility to divest 
quickly 
if we cant be ready to hear the voices of blacks crying for 
justice above the call of profit yield then it doesnt mean 
anything to belong to the body of christ said the rev joseph w 
ellwanger of milwaukee 
the assembly is the first for the 53 millionmember denomination 
since the merger jan 1 1988 of the lutheran church in america 
the american lutheran church and the association of evangelical 
lutheran churches 
late saturday the assembly called for an end to us military 
aid to central america and of all destabilizing military 
involvement by outside nations 
the rev mary ann mollergunderson of madison wis said 
violence has increased in el salvador 
the resolution backed peace efforts by the central american 
governments themselves and urged relief and development aid for the 
region and lifting of the us economic embargo against nicaragua 
the denominations pension board holds 16 billion in 
investments for about 26000 participants mostly clergy 5700 of 
them already retired and on pensions 
kapanke said that since early 1988 the board had reduced 
investments in companies operating in south africa from 152 million 
to 849 million 
we think we are one of the leading denominations in 
divestment he said but we are required by law to manage the 
fund solely in the interest of members with care skill prudence 
and dilegence 
that demands financial caution he said in an interview he said 
divestment carried out without fiduciary considerations could mean 
a loss 
however the justice group argues that for the church the 
notion of prudent investment takes on a deeper theological meaning 
of faithfulness 
the boards fiduciary responsibility requires it to take into 
account not only economic factors but also the gospel of jesus 
christ and the churchs overwhelming opposition to investment in 
south africa the group has said 
a church should be willing to sacrifice and take risks to end 
apartheid said bishop david w olson of minneapolis 
it is possible it could mean a financial sacrifice even if it 
costs it should be done for moral reasons he said 
several denominations including the united church of christ 
the episcopal church the church of the brethren and the quakers 
have decided to sell all stock in companies operating in south 
africa but are not yet totally divested 
the justice group pointed out that the episcopal church and the 
united church of chris have have active nobuy policies for such 
stock and have made more progress in divesting than the lutheran 
denomination 
its pension board has had a passive and partial divestment 
policy the group says and actually has increased indirect 
investments in companies in south africa 
fortyfour of the denominations 65 regional synods have urged 
the board to divest totally from firms doing business in south 
africa some synods set a jan 1 1991 deadline for this to be 
accomplished 
</TEXT>
