more than 1000 jewish holocaust 
survivors sunday called on pope john paul ii to remove a 
controversial carmelite convent from a building at the site of the 
auschwitz concentration camp 
a statement released by the american gatheringfederation of 
jewish holocaust survivors meeting at browns hotel in sullivan 
county said vatican silence on the issue was reminiscent of papal 
inaction during world war ii when more than six million jews died 
in the holocaust 
benjamin meed president of the american gathering said the 
presence of the carmelite nuns at the site angered jews and that 
they had set up symbols of faith holy to them but alien to most of 
those who perished at auschwitz 
the nuns have been the subject of protests by jewish groups for 
about two years catholic leaders signed an accord with jewish 
leaders agreeing to remove the group by feb 22 1989 but the nuns 
are still in the building in oswiecim poland a few feet from the 
fence surrounding the concentration camp 
the statement to the pope read in part you lived in the 
vicinity of auschwitz during the years of the holocaust you know of 
the murders at auschwitz surely you know that the overwhelming 
majority of the victims were jews killed solely because they were 
sons and daughters of the jewish people their memory must be 
honored their identity affirmed 
neither a convent nor a synagogue should be on the grounds of 
auschwitz the holy martyrs of auschwitz should be left 
undisturbed the statement said 
