<TEXT>
tropical storm felix moved slowly across the eastern 
atlantic on sunday with top winds of 50 mph but posed no threat to 
land forecasters said 
felix the sixth named storm of the 1989 atlantic hurricane 
season formed saturday in the cape verde islands off western africa 
even as tropical storm erin faded far to the north without touching 
land 
at 1030 pm edt sunday the center of felix was near latitude 
192 north longitude 247 west or about 200 miles northwest the 
cape verde island of sal said forecasters at the national hurricane 
center in suburban coral gables 
it was moving north northwest near 7 mph and was expected to 
maintain that course through the day maximum sustained winds were 
at 50 mph with higher gusts in squalls the storm was expected to 
continue this motion monday said hurricane specialist hal gerrish 
erin the third hurricane of the season also was spawned off the 
tip of western africa it became a tropical storm aug 19 and 
reached hurricane strength on tuesday but was downgraded saturday 
as it moved over cold waters 800 miles west of ireland 
a tropical depression becomes a named storm when sustained winds 
reach 39 mph and a hurricane if winds climb to 74 mph 
the atlantic hurricane season runs from june 1 to nov 30 
</TEXT>
